Molecular Ecology Workgroup, Goethe University Frankfurt/Main, Germany, Applied Bioinformatics Group, School of Agriculture and Food Sciences, University of Queensland,

flowRoot.flowPara: Direct-To-Consumer (DTC) genetic testing, as offered by companies such as 23andMe or deCODEme, has been on the rise in the last couple of years: Around 200,000 people worldwide have had their genomes tested by such DTC services [1]. Those services usually check for Single Nucleotide Polymorphisms (SNPs) using microarrays, though Exome sequencing services are also currently entering the market [2]. Many of those DTC customers allow their service providers to use the data for in-house research.

If only a small fraction of DTC customers would make their data publicly available, a rich and free data resource for scientists all over the world could be created. Thus we evaluated the interest in sharing among DTC customers and set out to build a platform to enable sharing of DTC genotype data along with phenotypes.

We contacted customers of DTC genetic testing and people who are planning on becoming a customer of DTC genetic testing for our survey through the 23andMe community forums, various blogs which focus on personal genomics and social media platforms, such as Facebook and Twitter. 229 people responded to the survey, with about 40% of them already being customers of a DTC genetic testing company and about 30% planning on doing DTC genetic testing in the future.

Following the positive response from the genome sharing survey, we created a web platform (see Figure 2 for a screenshot) which enables DTC customers to share their genotype data along with phenotype data. The application is based on Ruby on Rails and utilises PostgreSQL as database backend. Users can directly upload genotyping data from 23andMe, deCODEme and FamilyTreeDNA as well as exome/genome VCF-files. Personal phenotypes can be entered in text form or automatically collected through the Fitbit quantified self tracking tool [3].

The SNPs listed on openSNP are annotated using the APIs from different sources and range from primary literature to manually curated sources like the GET Evidence Database of the Personal Genome Project [4]. Data can be exported from openSNP using a diverse array of export- and dump-methods. Additionally, a JSON API and the Distributed Annotation System [5] standard are offered. An overview on the input-sources and the output-methods can be seen in Figure 3.

Between the start of openSNP on 27.09.2011 and 27.10.2012 633 people have signed up for an account. In total 270 genetic data sets have been uploaded by the users. Those users also have provided a total of 4743 entries on 130 different phenotypes, which range from hair- and eye-colour to political beliefs. Figure 4 shows the growth over time.

The application can be found at https://opensnp.org and the code is released under MIT License. All data uploaded to openSNP is released under Creative Commons Zero, which is equivalent to the Public Domain in many countries. Currently we're working on adding support for the upload of full genome GFF files and the ability to create phenotypes which include binary data, for example photos, as variations instead of plain text.
